On Thursday 02 June 2005 08:59, jason r tibbetts wrote:
&gt; So far, so good. But what&#39;s a good way to handle this when the CUT
&gt; implements multiple interfaces, each of which has an abstract base
&gt; test? 

I faced the same problem a few days ago.

It maybe was a little worse, because the interfaces are interfaces in a 
framework and I wanted to provide an abstract test from which users of 
the framework could derive and have their objects tested against basic 
assumptions the framework has. 

I wanted just one test case, because I could not even be sure that future 
users will write any tests at all and I didn&#39;t want to scare them by 
pushing two or three tests on them.

I came up with a solution like this:

Have the tests as static public members that take the object under test as 
an argument. 

public class FooCheck extends TestCase {
	public static void doTestXyz(ObjectUnderTest o) {
		...
	}
}

These tests were sometimes more complex than I wanted them to be, so I had 
tests for these tests.

public class FooCheckTest extends TestCase {
	public void testDoesFooXyzCorrectly() {
		Object o = new ...;
		FooCheck.doTestXzy(o);
	}
}

The actual abstract test case then has one liners that call the static 
methods in the real checking class:

public abstract class AbstractFrameworkObjectTest extends TestCase {
	public abstract Object getObjectUnderTest();

	public void testXyz() {
		FooCheck.doTestXyz(getObjectUnderTest());
	}
}

Seems to work pretty well.

However, I like your inner classes idea as well.

Robert
